Week 2: Regression and model validation

## [1] "Sun Dec 05 19:02:40 2021"

The data used in this task is a subset of Learning 2014 survey data, collected by Kimmo Vehkalahti for an international survey of Approaches to Learning, made possible by Teachers Academy funding for Kimmo Vehkalahti in 2013-2015. The purpose of this exercise is to fit a linear regression model to the dataframe and try out model validation.

There are 166 observations of 7 variables in the dataframe. Variables used are gender (gender), age (age), attitude (attitude), deep questions (deep), strategic questions (stra), surface questions (surf) and exam points (points). Deep, stra and surf are combined variables from several related questions in the survey, which were scaled by taking the mean, and attitude a sum of 10 questions, which was scaled by dividing by the sum of the questions to the original Likert scale of 1-5. Points values of 0 have been excluded from the dataframe.

Creating a regression model

For closer inspection variables age, attitude and surf were selected to explain the target variable points

However, the dataset is a subset to begin with, and the respondent students have a wide array of other factors impacting their exam points. In this light, the low R-squared is acceptable.

Model diagnostics

To visualize the model diagnostics, the model is presented by Residuals vs Fitted values, Normal QQ-plot and Residuals vs Leverage.

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(my_model, which = c(1, 2, 5))

In the Residuals vs.Fitted graph the variance of the residuals is reasonably constant, implying that the size of the errors should not depend on the explanatory variables. The Normal Q-Q plot confirms the assumption that the errors of the model are normally distributed. By observing the residuals vs.leverage plot, no single observation stands out, and the leverage seems regular.

## [1] "Sun Dec 05 19:02:53 2021"

This week Im analysing a joined dataset that includes two student alcohol consumption data sets. Data set information can be found here: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Student+Performance The following adjustments have been made: The variables not used for joining the two data have been combined by averaging (including the grade variables)

  • alc_use is the average of Dalc (weekday alcohol usage) and Walc (weekend alcohol usage).
  • high_use is TRUE if alc_use is higher than 2 and FALSE otherwise.

The purpose of my analysis is to study the relationships between high/low alcohol consumption and some of the other variables in the data.

There are 370 observations over 35 variables. Respondents are studens whose age range from 15 to 22 years, and there are numeric, nominal and binary variables. Binary variables include questions such as students sex (F for female, M for male), the school they are from (school), family size (famsize).

Looking more closely at 4 variables in relation to alcohol consumption:

I believe that it will be interesting to further study these 4 specific variables and how they relate to alcohol consumption.

  • variable school because peer pressure can affect alcohol consumption.
  • variable famsize which is a binary variable of less than 3 family members or more than 3 family members. My hypothesis is that family size does not predict alcohol consumption.
  • variable age because there is a legal age (lets say its 18 for this dataset) for using alcohol, and some of the respondents in the data are below 18 years old.
  • variable absences, number of school absences (numeric: from 0 to 93) because other norm-breaking behavior such as absences from school may occur if student is also consuming alcohol regularly.

Here is an overview of the four variables in the dataset:

Family size matters for female students more, but more alcohol using male students come from bigger (GT3) families whereas female students alcohol usage is lower than males in any case. As expected, school matters, but it seems that the effect is limited to male students, who use use alcohol more than female students. Among female students there is no difference between schools. From the data we can see that the absences do not seem to have a specific influence on alcohol consumption. The surprising result is that most alcohol using female students seem to be 16-17 years of age, whereas male students report using alcohol until they are 18. This relates either to the fact that the legal age of alcohol consumption is 16 (as there are only few observations of below 16 years old using alcohol) and that after the initial one or two years of legal consumption, the usage lessens significantly.

Predictive power of the model

The only variable with a statistically significant connection to high alcohol usage is absences. Ill explore its prediction capabilities next. Lets look at the cross tabulation of the prediction versus actual values of high usage:

# fit the model
m2 <- glm(high_use ~ absences, data = alc, family = "binomial")

# predict() the probability of high_use
probabilities <- predict(m2, type = "response")

# add the predicted probabilities to 'alc'
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = (probability > 0.5))

# see the last ten original classes, predicted probabilities, and class predictions
select(alc, absences, high_use, probability, prediction) %>% tail(10)

Based on this confusion matrix, the prediction is surprisingly good at predicting lack of high usage (true positives 0,68 of 0,96 and true negatives 0,024 of 0.038). If we assume that by guessing only, we would get it right 50 % of the time, the predictive model is much better than just guessing.

Prediction error comparison

# define a loss function (average prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

# compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2891892
# K-fold (10-fold) cross-validation
cv <- cv.glm(data = alc, cost = loss_func, glmfit = m, K = 10)

# average number of wrong predictions in the cross validation
cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.2783784

The prediction error is less than 0,29 (actual: 0.2891892) for each observation in the training data. The 10-fold cross-validation diminishes the error by very little, result bein 0,2837838 which is a difference of 0,0054054 or ~0.005. As the Datacamp prediction error was 0,26, we can see that my model was worse by two hairs (around 0,02). As this is most likely result from choice of variables, I can say that choosing some other variables with statistical significance would have improved my results. At this point, Im not going to try to find a better suited model.

In the matrix above, the bigger and darker the circle, the stronger the correlation between variables. The correlation matrix shows that there is a strong correlation between age and nox (nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million)). Chas is a dummy variable (Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)) and therefore it is not surprising that there are very little correlation between chas and the other variables.

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# plot the lda results
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes) + title("LDA biplot")
## integer(0)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 2)

From the cross tabulation presented above we can see that there is a significant amount of misclassification related to lower to medium levels of criminality, but the high crime rate is predicted much more accurately with only single misclassifications. This may be understandable from the assumption that high crime is generally better recognized and subsequently recorded, whereas low crime rates imply fewer observations of crime.

Running k-means algorithm on the data:

Now investigating what is the optimal number of clusters:

# change the object to data frame
boston_scaled2 <- as.data.frame(boston_scaled2)

# determine the k
set.seed(123)

# determine the number of clusters
k_max <- 10

# calculate the total within sum of squares
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(boston_scaled2, k)$tot.withinss})

# visualize the results
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

There is a big drop in similarity between the clusters at about 2, so the optimal number of clusters is 2. Running the k-means clustering algorithm with 2 clusters on the boston_scaled2 data:

# run k-means clustering algorithm again 
km <-kmeans(boston_scaled2, centers = 2)

# plot the boston_scaled2 dataset with clusters
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
pairs(boston_scaled2[1:5], col = km$cluster)

pairs(boston_scaled2[6:10], col = km$cluster)

pairs(boston_scaled2, col = km$cluster)

The dummy variable chas is distinguished by the almost complete lack of overlap between the clusters. Age and pupil-teacher ratio per town (ptratio). Crime rate variation correlates with human variables such as age, black, lstat (lower status of population), which is not surprising.

It looks like there is very little correlation between the variables Parli.F and Labo.FM with the other variables. Most understandably there is strong correlation between Life.Exp and Edu.Exp, as we can assume that both life expectancy and years of secondary education are affected by general living standards and well-being. Accordingly, a strong negative correlation is shown between Mat.Mor and Life.Exp. GNIs correlation with the variables is in general surprisingly weak, when we think that Gross National Income would play a role in the general living standards.

Standardized dataset. Variables affecting the Human Development Index

Now the variance captured by PC1 is only around 50% and PC2 around 16%, which evens out the variation caused by other components, while we are still able to say that the variation is mainly caused by the two first components. The results are different with standardized and non-standardized data. The non-standardized data mapped on the biplot only show the first two principal components, as they together explain almost all of the variance. Sub-saharan African countries are singled out. The standardized data analyzed with PCA on the other hand shows that more factors explain the variance. Northern Europe stands out as a cluster, explained by Parliamentary representation, ratio of F/M labour and expected years of secondary education.
